div.div: This is a medium sized assemblage, consisting of a >4mm dry sieved fraction and >4mm flot (S2, 100%, flot No.7046). Dry sieved fraction: This is a moderately processed assemblage consisting mainly of sheep-sized animals, with only a few cattle-sized pieces. The diagnostics are overwhelmingly caprine, with a few remains of fox. Body part distribution: Sheep-size animals - almost all body parts represented, although there are low numbers of rib, vertebrae and phalanges. Two caudal vertebrae are articulated. Diagnostics: >30% of elements are diagnostic. In my experience this is higher than usual. Diagnostic elements are predominantly caprine. Among these, there are a lot of teeth, though not a lot of other cranial remains. Forelimbs, hindlimbs, and feet are all present,but very few phalanges. The mandibles, teeth and radii suggest a caprine MNI of two. Also a mandible, calcaneum and metatarsal of fox are present. Cow-sized animals are limited to fragments of one long bone, one rib, a few skull parts, one tibia and one sesamoid. Fragmentation: Generally this assemblage has large pieces compared to many Catalhoyuk assemblages. The modal size (~60% of the assemblage) of the full assemblage is 3 - 5 cm, with a size range from 2- 12 cm. Excluding the diagnostics, particularly the teeth, the modal size shifts to 5 - 7 cm. Burning: very little indeed, only 8 pieces at low temperature (sheep-sized: five long bones, one scapula fragment and two indeterminate; cattle-sized: one long bone fragment). Also one sheep-sized rib is calcined. Gnawing: Carnivore gnawing is present but <5%. Digestion: Also present: ~ 5 pieces. Surface condition : >95% moderately weathered (level 3), with the rest at level 4. Integrity/coherence: Fragmentation patterns plus body part representation suggests food consumption waste, with some primary butchery evidence. Burning, gnawing, digestion and surface condition all suggest relatively short exposure time before burial, with little redeposition. There is little coherence to the assemblage, other than that it is food processing waste with a few cattle-sized pieces indicating some mixing. Overall assessment: A relatively undisturbed midden deposit consisting primarily of food processing remains. Flot (Sample 2 >4mm, 100% flot No.7046): The flot compares well to the dry sieved fraction in the balance of burning, digestion and gnawing. There are mainly sheep-sized remains of long bone fragments, vetebrae and very few ribs. The diagnostic elements in this size-class are mainly the smaller and younger bones of sheep/goat/roe deer - incisors, carpals and tarsals, unfused ends and epiphyses of metapodials and phalanges The mature sheep/goat diagnostics include fore and hind limbs, cranial, scapular and pelvic pieces. Continuing in the sheep-sized class, there is a diagnostic medium canid carnassial and astragalus but no further elements. There is one worked piece - F219. Last record:249
